@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

                       @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}


I've spent a lot trying to use the HP LajertJet 4 connected to my Amiga with
my brother's pc without great success, I've tried some of the tools available
on Aminet but none satisfing...

Finally on the great ML for the Amiga port of Samba I've got some info and
decided to prepare these two scripts

     @{b}LPR@{ub} prints to PAR: a spoolfile received with Samba and then deletes the
         file

     @{b}LPQ@{ub} simply returns OK as "queue status". Any info on how to improve
         this is welcome...
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

                            @{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}


- Copy the two scripts LPR and LPQ into your Samba: assign

- Be sure the S flag is active, @{b}protect Samba:LP? +s@{ub}

- Create a directory @{b}Spools@{ub} inside @{b}Samba:@{ub} and then create another directory
  called as the @{b}printer name@{ub} in smb.conf (Mine is called @{b}hplj4@{ub} so I've
  created the directory @{b}Samba:Spools/hplj4@{ub})

- Manually or using SWAT edit your printer configuration adding these three
  commands in smb.conf

      path = /Samba/Spools/%S
      print command = /Samba/LPR %s %p
      lpq command = /Samba/LPQ %p

- Add this command to your [printers] sections

      path = /samba/spools

- Add this command to your [global] sections

      printcap name = /Samba/Spools/printcap

- Edit the above file adding a row with the printer name as configured in
  your smb.conf (Mine is called hplj4 so I've one row with hplj4 in it)



As an example here you are how I've configured my HP LaserJet 4L

[printers]
    comment = All Printers
    path = /samba/spools
    printable = Yes
    browseable = No

[hplj4]
    comment = HP LaserJet 4L
    path = /Samba/Spools/%S
    writeable = Yes
    create mask = 0700
    guest ok = Yes
    printable = Yes
    print command = /Samba/LPR %s %p
    lpq command = /Samba/LPQ %p
    lprm command = /s/lprm -P%p %j
    printer driver = HP LaserJet 4L
@endnode

